args: I'm sorry, sir, but the restaurant isn't\nopen yet. Might I suggest you—
Listen... I'm sorry for yelling at you\nlike I did.
It's okay. I came back because\nI couldn't let it go either.
To this day, my heart still aches\nknowing the princess died\nwith an empty stomach.
You were right, Valerio. I used her lost\nsense of taste as an excuse to stop trying.
If only I'd had more skill as a chef,\nmaybe things could have ended\ndifferently...
I feel like the only way I'll ever bury\nthis regret is by cooking now what I\ncouldn't then.

I want to study under you—the man
who's become the greatest chef in the
world—and ascend to greater culinary
heights. Please... I'm begging you!
I want you to cook the princess's favorite\ndish—right here, right now. I will taste it,\nand make my decision accordingly.
I think I'm a little confused.
All right. Then if you don't mind me\nusing your kitchen and ingredients,\nI'll get started.
Hey, wait a minute!\nWhat the heck is going on?
Heh. Looks like we showed up right\nin the middle of a job interview.
Feels more like a wake than an interview...\nThank Heavens you guys showed up to\nhelp lift all this gloom!
We were really just stopping by to\ndrop off some of the vegetables we\nharvested...
Aw, we got time to spare! And besides,\nthey said they'd let us try this guy's grub!
I must admit, I'm curious to see how\nValerio reacts. And if another fight breaks\nout, we should probably be here to stop it.
Just a few finishing touches, and...
Holy veg-a-roni! Is that a vegetable stew?\nIt smells fantastic!
So you do remember Her Highness's\nfavorite dish. But of course, the proof\nis in the pudding—or stew, in this case.
I'm confident in my work. I've been\ntraining tirelessly all this time.
Is that so? Well, let's try it.
Don't mind if I do.\nMmm... This is great!

Wow! It's packed with all sorts of veggies,
and each one feels like it's contributing
to the overall flavor profile. There's real
craftsmanship here.
Hm... This isn't the way it used to taste.
Does that mean he doesn't get the job?
It's different now. And by ＂different,＂\nI mean unmistakably superior.
It's good to see that you haven't\nbeen resting on your laurels.
Yes. The job is his, if he wants it.\nBut I warn you: I will not stand for\nanything less than your best.
Closing time at last. Thank you for\nhelping out again today, Mitsuba.
Hey, thank YOU for giving me another\nopportunity to steal all your secrets!
I believe the proper way to express that\nsentiment would be to thank me for my\nguidance, but suit yourself.
Now, then—any requests for tonight's\nstaff meal? I'm all ears.
Easy. I want the princess's favorite dish.
What? I'm just curious to try your\nversion of it, Valerio.
The vegetable stew the new guy made\nhad a very complex, but gentle flavor.
I can tell how much she still means\nto you both.
Indeed. I will never forget her.
Doesn't it hurt to hold\non to those feelings?
Of course. But I'm prepared to embrace\nthat pain for the rest of my days.
Is that why you hired that guy?\nTo keep your past close at hand?
My memories of the princess are not\nsomething to forget, or to move past.
They will forever bring me warmth,\nas well as tears.
Anyway, it will be good to have him here.\nI need the help, and he's not a bad cook.
Atta boy! You know what that is? Growth.
I appreciate you saying so. Now,\ntake a seat and prime your taste\nbuds for something truly remarkable.
Thanks again for this opportunity.\nI'm excited to start working with you.
The feeling is mutual. Now, shall we?\nWe have a restaurant to run!
Look, they just opened!\nCome on, Mommy, hurry up!\nI'm staaarving!
(No matter how many restaurants I open,\nthere are flavors I will never, ever forget.)

(I can only hope that my cooking here
will touch people's hearts the way
Her Highness once touched mine.
Bon appétit, everyone.)
